  "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
  "body": "This issue was born out of the discussion from https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/issues/54904 and https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/pull/56702. \r\n\r\nIn short:\r\nJob controller has an exponential backoff in place when failures happen to a job. As long as the parallelism is one, it's clear when a failure or success happens, the latter clears the backoff. The problem is when parallelism > 1, which can lead to situation where the controller can observe successful and failed pod at the same time and won't clear the backoff leading to further retries and longer wait times (see https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/issues/54904 for extensive details about the problem in e2e)\r\n\r\nPossible solutions:\r\n\r\n1. leave everything as is\r\n2. when both success and failure are observed clear the backoff\r\n\r\nPros and cons:\r\n\r\nAd. 1.\r\nAside from (https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/issues/54904) I wonder if users got affected by it. Does it make sense to fix it at all?\r\n\r\nAd. 2.\r\nThis approach make sense in some situation, but the question arise, should that be controlled by a user. What if I have 9 failures and 1 success (parallelism = 10), should I still clear the backoff? Maybe we should introduce user controller field to set the failure rate in this case. \r\n",
